"Hullé M., Coeur d'Acier A., Bankhead-Dronnet S., Harrington R.","Aphids in the face of global changes",2010,"Comptes Rendus - Biologies","333","6-7",,"497","503",,,10.1016/j.crvi.2010.03.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956626798&partnerID=40&md5=c75d26cf6883302f5a5e3958568cda40","Unité mixte de recherche (BiO3P), Institut national de la recherche agronomique, BP 35327, 35653 Le-Rheu cedex, France; INRA, UMR CBGP, Campus international de Baillarguet, CS 30016, 34988 Montferrier-sur-Lez cedex, France; UPRES EA 1207 (LBLGC), Facultédes sciences, Université d'Orléans, Rue de Chartres, 45067 Orléans, France; Centre for Bioenergy and Climate Change, Department of Plant and Invertebrate Ecology, Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom","Hullé, M., Unité mixte de recherche (BiO3P), Institut national de la recherche agronomique, BP 35327, 35653 Le-Rheu cedex, France; Coeur d'Acier, A., INRA, UMR CBGP, Campus international de Baillarguet, CS 30016, 34988 Montferrier-sur-Lez cedex, France; Bankhead-Dronnet, S., UPRES EA 1207 (LBLGC), Facultédes sciences, Université d'Orléans, Rue de Chartres, 45067 Orléans, France; Harrington, R., Centre for Bioenergy and Climate Change, Department of Plant and Invertebrate Ecology, Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom","Global warming is one of the principal challenges facing insects worldwide. It affects individual species and interactions between species directly through effects on their physiology and indirectly through effects on their habitat. Aphids are particularly sensitive to temperature changes due to certain specific biological features of this group. Effects on individuals have repercussions for aphid diversity and population dynamics. At a pan- European scale, the EXAMINE observation network has provided evidence for an increase in the number of aphid species present over the last 30 years and for earlier spring flights. We review these results and provide a review of the principal effects of global warming on aphid communities. © 2010 Académie des sciences.","Biodiversity; Carbon dioxide; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Natural enemies; Ozone; Phenology","carbon dioxide; ozone; carbon dioxide; ozone; aphid; carbon dioxide; European Union; flight; global warming; natural enemy; phenology; physiological response; population dynamics; species diversity; temperature effect; aphid; biodiversity; global change; greenhouse effect; host; nonhuman; phenology; plant; population dynamics; review; species diversity; species habitat; spring; temperature sensitivity; adaptation; animal; greenhouse effect; physiology; temperature; Aphididae; Hexapoda; Adaptation, Physiological; Animals; Aphids; Biodiversity; Carbon Dioxide; Global Warming; Ozone; Temperature",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; ozone, 10028-15-6; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"(2007), p. 104. , IPCC, Contribution of Working Groups I, II and III to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, in: Core Writing Team, R.K. Pachauri, A. Reisinger (Eds.), Climate change 2007: Synthesis report, IPCC, Geneva, SwitzerlandCannon, R.J.C., The implications of predicted climate change for insect pests in the UK, with emphasis on non-indigenous species (1998) Global Change Biol., 4, pp. 785-796; McCarty, J., Ecological consequences of recent climate change Conserv (2001) Biol., 15, pp. 320-331; Root, T.L., Price, J.T., Hall, K.R., Schneider, S.H., Rosenzweigk, C., Pounds, J.A., Fingerprints of global warming on wild animals and plants (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 57-60; Heie, O.E., Why are there so few aphids in the temperate area of the southern hemisphere? (1994) Eur. J. Entomol., 91, pp. 127-133; Strathdee, A.T., Howling, G.G., Bale, J.S., Cold hardiness of overwintering aphid eggs (1995) J. Insect Physiol., 41, pp. 653-657; Kilian, L., Nielson, M.W., Differential effects of temperature on the biological act